Golden Gate Park is similar in shape but 20% larger than New York's Central Park.
With 23 miles of ladders and 300,000 rivets in each tower, the Golden Gate Bridge was the world's longest span when it opened in 1937.
In 1893, chocolatier Domingo Ghirardelli bought an entire city block to house the headquarters of Ghirardelli Chocolates.

Founded in 1853, 3 years after California joined the United States, the Academy was originally named the California Academy of Natural Sciences and was the first institution of its kind in the United States.
United Nations Plaza was built in 1975 and across its walkways are white lines into which the preamble to the preamble of the UN charter is carved.
SF General Hospital is the only Level I Trauma Center serving San Francisco and northern San Mateo County.
The original Palace was built for the 1915 Panama-Pacific Exposition, and completely destroyed in 1964. It was rebuilt in 1965.

Before the 1906 earthquake, the land on which Marina Green sits was a tidal marsh, and rubble from the earthquake was dumped on the site. However, the site was filled in to provide land for the 1915 Panama-Pacific Exhibition.

Built in 1853, Fort Point is the only West Coast fort built by the Union Army. Though the Confederate army planned to attack San Francisco, the commanding Confederate general learned that the war had ended while end route to SF.

The Conservatory, unveiled in 1879, is the oldest public conservatory in the Western Hemisphere.
Built in 1924, the Legion of Honor is a 3/4 replica of the Parisian Palais de la Legion d'Honneur.
Lombard Street is not actually the most crooked in SF. That honor goes to Potrero Hill's Vermont Street between 22nd and 23rd.
Tennis courts now sit on the site; in the movie the structure was Carlota Valdes' home.
An artificial island, Treasure Island was created for the 1939 Golden Gate International Exposition, and is named after the novel by Robert Louis Stevenson, a one-time San Francisco resident.
